A renewal of the very American ideal that labour rights are human rights at the same time
Congressmen Keith Ellison and John Lewis have proposed a law that protects union organizing as a civil right.
"The way unions work, the way jobs work for the middle class", says Ellison, a Democratic senator from Minnesota who co-chairs the Congressional Committee.
That's why I'm so proud to be able to introduce a law that strengthens the status of employees, along with the occasional rights model John Lewis.
This groundbreaking legislation will give workers the same legal options to prevent discrimination in organizing unions as in other forms of discrimination - and will stop anti-union forces
To amend the Labour Relations Act to allow all workers who face discrimination to join unions to stand trial in civil court - and to award compensation or damages - is the right and necessary initiative.
But it's certainly not a radical initiative - at least not by American standards.
The best way to understand what Ellison, Lewis and other lawmakers are proposing is to re-engage with the American ideal.
Despite the trade union struggles that have taken place in recent years - in Wisconsin, Michigan and other states - Americans have once encouraged countries around the world to adopt, expand and respect labor rights.
There was a time, and millions of Americans still remember it, when the country was one breath, promoting democracy, freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and the right to assemble.
When the United States occupied Japan after World War II, General Douglas MacArthur and his advisers supported the country to adopt a constitution designed to ensure that Hideki Toya's military autocracy was replaced by democracy.
They believed that workers and their unions were playing a role in shaping a new Japan, they included language in them and they openly recognized that the right of workers to assemble, negotiate and act collectively was guaranteed.
When the United States occupied Germany after World War II, General Dwight David Eisenhower and his advisers urged the Germans to create a constitution that would ensure that Adolf Hitler's fascism was replaced by a strong democracy.
The Germans, aware that workers would need to be organized and promoted in the new nation, included a clause that openly states: The right to form associations that would secure and improve working and economic conditions will be guaranteed to every individual and to every profession or profession.
Any agreement which restricts or seeks to infringe this right shall be annulled.
When former First Lady Eleanor Roosevelt presided over the International Commission on Human Rights, which drafted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, which was adopted by the United Nations in 1948 as a universal treaty, the proponents and Roosevelt's guarantee that everyone has the right to form and join trade unions as part of protecting their interests included it.
Americans have been embracing the basic premise for generations that labor rights are human rights.
When countries advised other countries on how to build a civil and democratic society, Americans explained that the right to create unions - and their participation in collective bargaining with companies and government agencies as an equal partner - must be protected.
Now that these rights are being challenged in America, it is absolutely necessary to return to the American ideal that working people must have the right to organize and advocate in a free and open society.
As the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. said 50 years ago:
History is a great teacher.
Today, everyone knows that unions have not diminished the power of the nation, but have expanded it.
They raised the standard of living of millions, created a market for industry, and raised production to an unprecedented level.
Those who attack unions forget these simple truths, but history remembers them.
History doesn't forget, and neither should we.
The formal recognition of labour rights as human rights - and the extension of civil rights protection to prevent discrimination in trade union organisation - is very late.
Keith Ellison and John Lewis are restoring the ideals that elevated America and made it a true promise of democracy.
