Why can the universe be more than one dimension and we can't see it?
Physicists don't usually write bestsellers, but Brian Green of Columbia University hit the black in 1999.
His book, The Elegant Universe, became the most accessible way for lay people to penetrate the troublesome pile of problems that many theoretical physicists are now dealing with - a quest to unite two greatly functioning but incompatible discoveries of the 20th century: quantum theory and general relativity.
One of the reasons for the success of the Elegant Universe is undoubtedly that in the search for a unified physical theory, it's not a boring story.
The fundamental problem of physics between the two key theories (for at this point our universe is de facto divided into two worlds with different laws) has been solved and solved so imaginatively that it is worth telling even to the laity.
Greene also dealt with the complex material so freshly and engagingly that it is hard to say how much interesting he did not include in his book.
In addition, he largely corrected his "mistake" in two other books: The Structure of the Universe and The Hidden Reality.
Apparently, even the author would not object if his book were to become obsolete faster, but the fact is that even after 15 years, the elegant universe still provides almost everything essential that an informed layman with an ambition to understand the world should know about this important part of theoretical physics.
It's quite likely that in the coming years, there will be a bit more activity in this area after all (for example, because the LHC accelerator will finally go full gas), and so it's a good time to enter the Green, the nonviolently open door of the world of modern physics.
How big can our universe be?
The idea that our universe may have more than three dimensions of space may sound silly, fantastic, strange, or mystical.
Yet it is concrete and completely acceptable.
To understand this, let us for a moment turn our gaze away from the universe as a whole to something more earthly, specifically the long, thin garden hose for watering.
Imagine that you are pulling a 100-meter garden hose from one side of the canyon to the other, and you are watching the entire landscape from a half-mile away (as shown in the picture and on the next page).
From this distance, you can easily see a long, horizontal hose, but if you're not suffering from a sharp blink, you can barely tell the thickness of the hose.
Given its great distance from the pipe, you would think that the ant forced to live on the pipe has only one dimension in which to walk: the left-right dimension along the pipe.
If someone asks you where the ant was at the time, you can answer with one simple answer: the distance of the ant from the left (or right) end of the tube.
All we're saying is that from a half-mile away, a long piece of pipe looks like a one-dimensional object.
In the real world, the pipe is thick.
If we magnify everything, we suddenly see another dimension - a circle shaped like a tube that rolls.
From this magnification, it is clear that an ant can actually move in two independent dimensions: in the already well-known left-right dimension along the length of the tube, but also in the 'size in/against the direction of movement of the clock hands', around the circle diameter of the snake.
You're starting to understand that to determine the position of a small ant, you have to enter two numbers: how far away is the end of the tube and where is the looping tube on the circle.
This reflects the fact that the surface of the pipe is two-dimensional (experts will note that this chapter focuses purely on the fault theory of the string.
