The surface of the pipe is two-dimensional: one long longitudinal dimension is represented by a straight arrow, the dimension in the direction of the circle, marked by a circular arrow, is short and curved.
However, there is a clear difference between these two dimensions.
The diameter along the pipe is long and easily visible.
The diameter of the tube's rolling circuit is short, "sweaty" and less noticeable.
To realize the existence of a circular dimension, we had to study the pipes in much better resolution.
The above example illustrates an important feature of spatial dimensions.
That they're divided into two groups.
They can be either large, broad, and therefore directly visible, or small, convex and much worse observable.
Of course, in this case, we're not just going to jump to reveal the "scattered" dimension of the tube's thickness.
All you had to do was take a telescope to help.
But if the tube were thinner - like a hair or capillary - we would only reveal the dirty dimension with great effort.
In 1919, Kaluza sent Einstein his paper, in which he produced the stunning idea that the spatial geometry of the universe could have more than three dimensions we all know.
Kaluz argued his radical claim that the additional dimension provides an elegant and convincing framework within which Einstein's general relativity and Maxwell's electromagnetic theory can be drawn into a single, unified conceptual structure.
It immediately begs the question of how this Kaluz observation fits with the obvious fact that we see just three dimensions of space.
The answer, which Kaluza quietly assumed between the lines, and which was clearly stated and specified by Swedish mathematician Oskar Klein in 1926, stands and falls with the claim that the spatial geometry of our universe can have both large and curved dimensions.
This means that just like the dimensions of the length of a tube, our universe has three dimensions, big, wide and easily visible, that we are aware of at any moment.
But by analogy with the circular circuit of the garden hose, the universe can have additional dimensions, rigidly wrapped in space so small that they have been hidden from our most perfect experimental apparatus to date.
To get a clearer idea of the essence of Kaluz's remarkable proposal, let's stay with the pipeline for a while.
