Genetic disorders are often misdiagnosed
A woman in Britain describes how she thought she would die for many years after being misdiagnosed.
After being diagnosed with another disease, Karin Rodgers spent most of her adolescence thinking that she had only a few years to live.
It was actually Charcot-Marie-Tooth syndrome (CMT), a group of inherited disorders that damage the nerves outside the brain and spinal cord.
The charity CMT UK said that poor diagnosis is a common problem among people with CMT because very little is known about the disease.
It is estimated that approximately 23,000 people in the UK suffer from CMT, which can manifest motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, impaired walking and sprained toes.
In the case of those affected, numbness or pain may also occur, which is incurable and progressive, meaning that symptoms may worsen over time.
When Rodgers was 13, she thought she had Freidreich's ataxia, a disease that has a very poor prognosis.
She believed that before she celebrated her 18th birthday, she would be confined to a wheelchair, and dead by the time she was 30.
A mother of two, now 51, says: "As a child, I knew I couldn't do the same things as everyone else.
I fell every day and it took me longer.
I could never ride a roller or skateboard with other kids, and I was bullied at school for walking and running.
When Rodgers was 13, and she was after several surgeries that were supposed to release her Achilles tendons and straighten her legs, she took advantage of her doctor leaving the room, and looked into her file, where she learned she had FA.
"I felt guilty for following, so I didn't tell anyone, but when I got home, I looked up the information about the disease in the library and wrote to the FA", she says.
When they answered, I was shocked, I was totally panicked.
I thought by the time I was 18, I'd be in a wheelchair, and by the time I was 25, I'd be dead, and in the meantime, I'd gradually lose all my powers.
I was all alone and planning my funeral.
At 17, she realized that her walking ability had not deteriorated as much as she had expected, and she asked her surgeon.
He just stood up, hugged her and said, "Honey, I don't think you have the disease, otherwise you'd be in a wheelchair.
I think it'll be something much less life-threatening.
After passing several genetic tests, it was discovered that she had CMT.
"When he explained to me what CMT was, I thought I was a lucky kid", she said.
The charity CMT UK has launched a month of CMT awareness to raise awareness of the disease.
