Norwegian Cruise is approaching a $3 billion takeover of Prestige Cruise
According to sources familiar with the matter, Norwegian Cruise Line Holdings s.r.o. (NCHL.O.), the world's third largest cruise ship operator, has advanced the acquisition of Prestige Cruises International Inc. for approximately $3 billion.
The transaction would allow Norwegian Cruise, a company with a market value of $6.8 billion and competing with the greater competition of Royal Carrebian Cruises s.r.o. (RCL.N) and Carnival Corp. (CCL.N), access to Prestige Cruises luxury cruise ships and wealthy customers.
The deal could be made public this week, a source said on Sunday, but warned that negotiations may not yet end successfully.
The owner of Prestige Cruises, a private investment company Apollo Global Management LLC (APO.N), also owns a 20% stake in Norwegian Cruise.
Sources declined to be named because the negotiations are not public.
Norwegian Cruise and Prestige Cruises officials have not responded to requests for comment, and Apollo spokesman declined to comment.
Norwegian Cruise, based in Miami, operates 13 cruise ships in North America, the Mediterranean and Baltic Seas, Central America and the Caribbean.
The company's revenue in 2013 was $2.57 billion, up 13% from 2012.
Prestige Cruises operates under the brands Oceania and Regent, which together own eight cruise ships to Scandinavia, Russia, the Mediterranean, North America, Asia, Africa and South America.
The company reported sales of $1.2 billion in 2013, up 6% from the previous year.
The 29 billion-dollar segment of cruise shipping is expected to benefit from the rise of the middle class in emerging economies such as China and India over the coming year.
Companies are competing to make them the preferred choice for these customers when choosing cruise ships.
Prestige Cruises registered its first public offering with US regulators in January 2014.
Apollo has held a majority stake in the company since 2007 when it closed a $850 million deal.
Norwegian Cruise has existed in its current form since 2000, when it merged with the cruise operator owned by Genting Bhd (GENT.KL), a consortium of leisure businesses and casinos controlled by Malaysian billionaire Lim Kok Thay.
In 2008, Apollo invested $1 billion in Norwegian Cruise.
Norwegian Cruise listed its shares on the stock exchange in January 2013.
According to the registration with the regulatory authorities at the end of June, Genting owned a capital stake of 28%, Apollo 20% and private investment firm TPG Capital LP 8%.
According to the registration documentation, the first public tender covers Carnival, Royal Caribbean Cruises and Norwegian Cruise together, 82 percent of the North American passenger volume.
