Putin asks Kiev to open talks with eastern Ukraine on state sovereignty
According to Russian newspaper accounts, Russian President Vladimir Putin on Sunday called on the Ukrainian government to stop fighting separatists in the east of the country and immediately begin negotiations on the state sovereignty of the sequestered areas.
His spokesman Dmitry Peskov later explained that Putin's remarks did not mean to suggest that the areas of eastern Ukraine controlled by separatists would become part of Russia, but that their status within Ukraine should be reassessed so that the Russian-speaking area would be given the authority to protect its rights and interests.
Putin's call on the Kiev government to treat the pro-Russian rebels as equals is in line with a clear strategy that has followed since the unrest erupted five months ago: Help the separatists occupy territory and allow the Ukrainian government to grant the newly declared Novorussia de facto independence so that it can instead join the West with Russia.
In an interview with state TV's first channel, Putin condemned Ukrainian military actions aimed at reclaiming eastern Donetsk and Luhansk regions, which were seized by separatists in March and April after Moscow annexed the Crimea peninsula belonging to Ukraine on March 18.
The Kremlin and separatists have designated the recently occupied territories as "Novorossiya" or "New Russia", a term referring to the famous pre-revolutionary days of the Russian Empire.
Russian news agency Itar-Tass published Putin's words saying that anyone who believes peace talks are on the horizon is a prisoner of illusion because Ukrainian politicians have launched a campaign ahead of the October 26 parliamentary elections, while government forces are attacking civilians in separatist-held areas.
In the interests of the people living in these areas, we must immediately start meaningful negotiations not only on legal issues but also on the political organisation of society and the status of the sovereignty of the state of southeast Ukraine he declared.
Peskov said Putin's reference to state sovereignty was conceived in the context of wider autonomy, which the Kiev leadership has been dealing with for several months and which is intended to alleviate concerns in Russian-speaking areas about the threat to cultural and linguistic rights.
Peskov said that only the Ukrainian government could grant the necessary autonomy to the Eastern Region.
This is not a matter for negotiation between Ukraine and Russia, Peskov said, "because it is not a conflict between Russia and Ukraine, but an internal Ukrainian conflict".
The Kremlin's intervention, which was intended to correct the misinterpretation of Putin's remarks, highlighted the approach of Russia's leadership to resolve the separatist uprising in the east, which is different from the open occupation of Crimea, where most of the population of two million is ethnic Russians.
Moscow would have a much greater problem annexing Donetsk and Luhansk in eastern Ukraine, as most of the 6.5 million inhabitants are not Russians, and public opinion polls conducted before the conflict showed broad support for staying in Ukraine.
The autonomy that Russian diplomats have discussed in international forums would give the regional governments in Ukraine the power to determine their own trade agreements and international relations, essentially giving the Kremlin actual control over the territory that would link the Russian mainland to Crimea.
The Black Sea Peninsula annexed five months ago is home to the main Russian naval fleet, maritime trading base and historic coastal resorts.
The area between Russian Rostov and Crimea is also a centre of mining, factories and smelters that produce important components for the Russian military.
During his June 7 inaugural address, Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko proposed that Ukrainian legislators - after new elections - consider constitutional changes that would give the diverse regions more control over their finances and language status.
But this vision of autonomy is very different from the Kremlin and the separatists' vision that Moscow is accused of arming and inciting violence.
Putin's latest call to Kiev to treat separatists as equals followed another advance by the rebels last week after Russian troops and tanks from the formerly quiet region along the Sea of Azov invaded eastern Ukraine.
Separatists reinforced by Russia have taken control of Novoazovsk with such force that Ukrainian security authorities fear that this is a campaign to occupy strategic coastal territory as far as Crimea.
This has accelerated the massive civilian and military effort to fortify Mariupol, a port with a metallurgical combined capacity of 500,000 inhabitants, which lies between Novoazovsk and the narrow gateway to the Crimean peninsula.
Poroshenko spoke at a meeting of the European Union's top officials in Brussels on Saturday, calling for action to prevent further Russian aggression against Ukraine, a former Soviet republic that has been independent for 23 years.
We are approaching a point of no return, Poroshenko warned.
There are now thousands of foreign troops and hundreds of foreign tanks on the territory of Ukraine.
The EU summit has not taken any definitive steps - leaders are calling for further sanctions against Russia in the event of an unspecified escalation of the Ukrainian crisis.
Colonel Andriy Lysenko, spokesman for Ukraine's National Security and Defense Council, told reporters in Kiev on Saturday that Ukrainian troops had to withdraw from their positions in Ilovaysk after two columns of Russian armored vehicles and 1,000 military units penetrated the Donetsk region last week to support the besieged separatists.
The first of 63 reported Ukrainian soldiers captured in Ilovaisk during the Russian invasion were replaced by 10 Russian paratroopers captured a week ago in the Ukraine, Lysenko said on Sunday.
